HEMORRHAGIC SEPTICEMIA, CATTLE - MALAYSIA (02)
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail posting
<http://www.promed.org>
See Also
Hemorrhagic septicemia, cattle - Malaysia (Terengganu) 19991216202932
Date: Tue, 28 Dec 1999 17:17:02 +0800
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Malaysian News, 28 Dec 1999 [edited

The "hawar berdarah" (Hemorrhagic Septicemia) has claimed 4 buffaloes,
bringing the number of animals to have died from the disease so far to 13.
State Veterinary Services Director Dr Ibrahim Che Embong said although
livestock breeders had been briefed on the disease, it still occurred, with
the latest cases detected in Bukit Tunggal mukim on 23 Dec 1999. "Eleven of
the animals were buffaloes while the rest were cows and some calves," he
said when contacted here today.
Dr Ibrahim said the disease was first detected in Kampung Bukit Tunggal on
4 Dec 1999 and later spread to Kampung Gong Tok Kandis, Kampung Conang and
Kampung Pengkalan Atap. He said the department had taken various measures
to keep the disease from spreading but to no effect since the livestock
breeders refused to cooperate.
Dr Ibrahim said the department feared the disease could spread to other
areas if the livestock breeders did not tie their animals. He said the
department would send its officers to Kampung Bukit Tunggal to immunize the
animals against the deadly disease.
There are 537 cows and 61 buffaloes in Kampung Bukit Tunggal.
Besides immunization to prevent widespread occurrences of the disease, the
department also restricted movement of animals from the infected area to
other areas.
